00:13:28.710 --> 00:13:28.720
Oh, okay. So, let me explain to you what

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:30.870
I'm doing in that case. I work on

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:33.190
PufferLib. PufferLib is a reinforcement

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:34.790
learning library that is very, very

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:35.990
fast.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.470
Um we do research on new algorithms. We

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:42.070
write lots of simulations.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:45.270
We do a lot of custom infrastructure.

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:47.190
Everything is kind of co-optimized

00:13:47.200 --> 00:13:49.750
around being very fast. And this means

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:52.710
that now you can do with PufferLib today

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:54.750
on one GPU at home

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:56.390
uh what used to take like a massive

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:59.030
cluster and a whole team in order to do

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:01.670
just 2 years ago. Uh the reason I sound

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:03.990
very annoyed is because this is like

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.670
right before release and I've been

00:14:06.680 --> 00:14:09.150
crunching for the last many weeks here

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:11.710
in order to get this thing out. And it's

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:13.670
a lot of just like fiddly pre-release

00:14:13.680 --> 00:14:16.710
work that is very, very boring and uh

00:14:16.720 --> 00:14:18.790
very irritating. And I'm pretty much

00:14:18.800 --> 00:14:20.910
ready to just have this thing done, take

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:22.670
a little bit of time off, and then

00:14:22.680 --> 00:14:24.390
prepare for the next work that's coming

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:26.470
up. Because we have all sorts of cool

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:27.750
plans for new research and new

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:29.670
algorithms, but I don't get to start any

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:32.190
